# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antibody-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] A **monoclonal antibody** (**mAb**, more rarely called **moAb**) is an antibody produced from a cell lineage made by cloning a unique white blood cell.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] All subsequent antibodies derived this way trace back to a unique parent cell.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Monoclonal antibodies are identical and can thus have monovalent affinity, binding only to a particular epitope (the part of an antigen that is recognized by the antibody).
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In contrast, polyclonal antibodies are mixtures of antibodies derived from multiple plasma cell lineages which each bind to their particular target epitope.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Artificial antibodies known as bispecific monoclonal antibodies can also be engineered which include two different antigen binding sites (FABs) on the same antibody.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] It is possible to produce monoclonal antibodies that specifically bind to almost any suitable substance; they can then serve to detect or purify it.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This capability has become an investigative tool in biochemistry, molecular biology, and medicine.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Monoclonal antibodies are used in the diagnosis of illnesses such as cancer and infections and are used therapeutically in the treatment of e.g. cancer and inflammatory diseases.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In the early 1900s, immunologist Paul Ehrlich proposed the idea of a *Zauberkugel* – "magic bullet", conceived of as a compound which selectively targeted a disease-causing organism, and could deliver a toxin for that organism.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This underpinned the concept of monoclonal antibodies and monoclonal drug conjugates.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Ehrlich and Élie Metchnikoff received the 1908 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine for providing the theoretical basis for immunology.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] By the 1970s, lymphocytes producing a single antibody were known, in the form of multiple myeloma – a cancer affecting B-cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These abnormal antibodies or paraproteins were used to study the structure of antibodies, but it was not yet possible to produce identical antibodies specific to a given antigen.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In 1973, Jerrold Schwaber described the production of monoclonal antibodies using human–mouse hybrid cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This work remains widely cited among those using human-derived hybridomas.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In 1975, Georges Köhler and César Milstein succeeded in making fusions of myeloma cell lines with B cells to create hybridomas that could produce antibodies, specific to known antigens and that were immortalized.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] They and Niels Kaj Jerne shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984 for the discovery.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In 1988, Gregory Winter and his team pioneered the techniques to humanize monoclonal antibodies, eliminating the reactions that many monoclonal antibodies caused in some patients.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] By the 1990s research was making progress in using monoclonal antibodies therapeutically, and in 2018, James P.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Allison and Tasuku Honjo received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discovery of cancer therapy by inhibition of negative immune regulation, using monoclonal antibodies that prevent inhibitory linkages.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The translational work needed to implement these ideas is credited to Lee Nadler.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] As explained in an NIH article, "He was the first to discover monoclonal antibodies directed against human B-cell–specific antigens and, in fact, all the known human B-cell–specific antigens were discovered in his laboratory.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Much of the work behind production of monoclonal antibodies is rooted in the production of hybridomas, which involves identifying antigen-specific plasma/plasmablast cells that produce antibodies specific to an antigen of interest and fusing these cells with myeloma cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Rabbit B-cells can be used to form a rabbit hybridoma.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Polyethylene glycol is used to fuse adjacent plasma membranes, but the success rate is low, so a selective medium in which only fused cells can grow is used.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This is possible because myeloma cells have lost the ability to synthesize hypoxanthine-guanine-phosphoribosyl transferase (HGPRT), an enzyme necessary for the salvage synthesis of nucleic acids.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The absence of HGPRT is not a problem for these cells unless the de novo purine synthesis pathway is also disrupted.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Exposing cells to aminopterin (a folic acid analogue which inhibits dihydrofolate reductase) makes them unable to use the de novo pathway and become fully auxotrophic for nucleic acids, thus requiring supplementation to survive.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The selective culture medium is called HAT medium because it contains hypoxanthine, aminopterin and thymidine.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This medium is selective for fused (hybridoma) cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Unfused myeloma cells cannot grow because they lack HGPRT and thus cannot replicate their DNA.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Unfused spleen cells cannot grow indefinitely because of their limited life span.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Only fused hybrid cells referred to as hybridomas, are able to grow indefinitely in the medium because the spleen cell partner supplies HGPRT and the myeloma partner has traits that make it immortal (similar to a cancer cell).
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This mixture of cells is then diluted and clones are grown from single parent cells on microtitre wells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The antibodies secreted by the different clones are then assayed for their ability to bind to the antigen (with a test such as ELISA or antigen microarray assay) or immuno-dot blot.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The most productive and stable clone is then selected for future use.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The hybridomas can be grown indefinitely in a suitable cell culture medium.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] They can also be injected into mice (in the peritoneal cavity, surrounding the gut).
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] There, they produce tumors secreting an antibody-rich fluid called ascites fluid.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The medium must be enriched during *in vitro* selection to further favour hybridoma growth.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This can be achieved by the use of a layer of feeder fibrocyte cells or supplement medium such as briclone.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Culture-media conditioned by macrophages can be used.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Production in cell culture is usually preferred as the ascites technique is painful to the animal.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Where alternate techniques exist, ascites is considered unethical.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Several monoclonal antibody technologies have been developed recently, such as phage display, single B cell culture, single cell amplification from various B cell populations and single plasma cell interrogation technologies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Different from traditional hybridoma technology, the newer technologies use molecular biology techniques to amplify the heavy and light chains of the antibody genes by PCR and produce in either bacterial or mammalian systems with recombinant technology.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] One of the advantages of the new technologies is applicable to multiple animals, such as rabbit, llama, chicken and other common experimental animals in the laboratory.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] After obtaining either a media sample of cultured hybridomas or a sample of ascites fluid, the desired antibodies must be extracted.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Cell culture sample contaminants consist primarily of media components such as growth factors, hormones and transferrins.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In contrast, the *in vivo* sample is likely to have host antibodies, proteases, nucleases, nucleic acids and viruses.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In both cases, other secretions by the hybridomas such as cytokines may be present.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] There may also be bacterial contamination and, as a result, endotoxins that are secreted by the bacteria.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Depending on the complexity of the media required in cell culture and thus the contaminants, one or the other method (*in vivo* or *in vitro*) may be preferable.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The sample is first conditioned, or prepared for purification.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Cells, cell debris, lipids, and clotted material are first removed, typically by centrifugation followed by filtration with a 0.45 μm filter.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These large particles can cause a phenomenon called membrane fouling in later purification steps.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In addition, the concentration of product in the sample may not be sufficient, especially in cases where the desired antibody is produced by a low-secreting cell line.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The sample is therefore concentrated by ultrafiltration or dialysis.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Most of the charged impurities are usually anions such as nucleic acids and endotoxins.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These can be separated by ion exchange chromatography.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Either cation exchange chromatography is used at a low enough pH that the desired antibody binds to the column while anions flow through, or anion exchange chromatography is used at a high enough pH that the desired antibody flows through the column while anions bind to it.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Various proteins can also be separated along with the anions based on their isoelectric point (pI).
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In proteins, the isoelectric point (pI) is defined as the pH at which a protein has no net charge.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] When the pH > pI, a protein has a net negative charge, and when the pH < pI, a protein has a net positive charge.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] For example, albumin has a pI of 4.8, which is significantly lower than that of most monoclonal antibodies, which have a pI of 6.1.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Thus, at a pH between 4.8 and 6.1, the average charge of albumin molecules is likely to be more negative, while mAbs molecules are positively charged and hence it is possible to separate them.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Transferrin, on the other hand, has a pI of 5.9, so it cannot be easily separated by this method.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] A difference in pI of at least 1 is necessary for a good separation.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Transferrin can instead be removed by size exclusion chromatography.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] This method is one of the more reliable chromatography techniques.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Since we are dealing with proteins, properties such as charge and affinity are not consistent and vary with pH as molecules are protonated and deprotonated, while size stays relatively constant.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Nonetheless, it has drawbacks such as low resolution, low capacity and low elution times.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] A much quicker, single-step method of separation is protein A/G affinity chromatography.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The antibody selectively binds to protein A/G, so a high level of purity (generally >80%) is obtained.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The generally harsh conditions of this method may damage easily damaged antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] A low pH can break the bonds to remove the antibody from the column.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In addition to possibly affecting the product, low pH can cause protein A/G itself to leak off the column and appear in the eluted sample.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Gentle elution buffer systems that employ high salt concentrations are available to avoid exposing sensitive antibodies to low pH.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Cost is also an important consideration with this method because immobilized protein A/G is a more expensive resin.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] To achieve maximum purity in a single step, affinity purification can be performed, using the antigen to provide specificity for the antibody.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In this method, the antigen used to generate the antibody is covalently attached to an agarose support.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] If the antigen is a peptide, it is commonly synthesized with a terminal cysteine, which allows selective attachment to a carrier protein, such as KLH during development and to support purification.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The antibody-containing medium is then incubated with the immobilized antigen, either in batch or as the antibody is passed through a column, where it selectively binds and can be retained while impurities are washed away.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] An elution with a low pH buffer or a more gentle, high salt elution buffer is then used to recover purified antibody from the support.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Product heterogeneity is common in monoclonal antibodies and other recombinant biological products and is typically introduced either upstream during expression or downstream during manufacturing.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These variants are typically aggregates, deamidation products, glycosylation variants, oxidized amino acid side chains, as well as amino and carboxyl terminal amino acid additions.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These seemingly minute structural changes can affect preclinical stability and process optimization as well as therapeutic product potency, bioavailability and immunogenicity.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The generally accepted purification method of process streams for monoclonal antibodies includes capture of the product target with protein A, elution, acidification to inactivate potential mammalian viruses, followed by ion chromatography, first with anion beads and then with cation beads.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Displacement chromatography has been used to identify and characterize these often unseen variants in quantities that are suitable for subsequent preclinical evaluation regimens such as animal pharmacokinetic studies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Knowledge gained during the preclinical development phase is critical for enhanced product quality understanding and provides a basis for risk management and increased regulatory flexibility.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The recent Food and Drug Administration's Quality by Design initiative attempts to provide guidance on development and to facilitate design of products and processes that maximizes efficacy and safety profile while enhancing product manufacturability.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The production of recombinant monoclonal antibodies involves repertoire cloning, CRISPR/Cas9, or phage display/yeast display technologies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Recombinant antibody engineering involves antibody production by the use of viruses or yeast, rather than mice.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These techniques rely on rapid cloning of immunoglobulin gene segments to create libraries of antibodies with slightly different amino acid sequences from which antibodies with desired specificities can be selected.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The phage antibody libraries are a variant of phage antigen libraries.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These techniques can be used to enhance the specificity with which antibodies recognize antigens, their stability in various environmental conditions, their therapeutic efficacy and their detectability in diagnostic applications.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Fermentation chambers have been used for large scale antibody production.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Recombinant DNA has been explored since the late 1980s to increase residence times.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In one approach called "CDR grafting", mouse DNA encoding the binding portion of a monoclonal antibody was merged with human antibody-producing DNA in living cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The expression of this "chimeric" or "humanised" DNA through cell culture yielded part-mouse, part-human antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Ever since the discovery that monoclonal antibodies could be generated, scientists have targeted the creation of *fully* human products to reduce the side effects of humanised or chimeric antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Several successful approaches have been proposed: transgenic mice, phage display and single B cell cloning.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Monoclonal antibodies are more expensive to manufacture than small molecules due to the complex processes involved and the general size of the molecules, all in addition to the enormous research and development costs involved in bringing a new chemical entity to patients.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] They are priced to enable manufacturers to recoup the typically large investment costs, and where there are no price controls, such as the United States, prices can be higher if they provide great value.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Once monoclonal antibodies for a given substance have been produced, they can be used to detect the presence of this substance.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Proteins can be detected using the Western blot and immuno dot blot tests.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In immunohistochemistry, monoclonal antibodies can be used to detect antigens in fixed tissue sections, and similarly, immunofluorescence can be used to detect a substance in either frozen tissue section or live cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Antibodies can also be used to purify their target compounds from mixtures, using the method of immunoprecipitation.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Therapeutic monoclonal antibodies act through multiple mechanisms, such as blocking of targeted molecule functions, inducing apoptosis in cells which express the target, or by modulating signalling pathways.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] One possible treatment for cancer involves monoclonal antibodies that bind only to cancer-cell-specific antigens and induce an immune response against the target cancer cell.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Such mAbs can be modified for delivery of a toxin, radioisotope, cytokine or other active conjugate or to design bispecific antibodies that can bind with their Fab regions both to target antigen and to a conjugate or effector cell.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Every intact antibody can bind to cell receptors or other proteins with its Fc region.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Monoclonal antibodies used for autoimmune diseases include infliximab and adalimumab, which are effective in rheumatoid arthritis, Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis and ankylosing spondylitis by their ability to bind to and inhibit TNF-α.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Basiliximab and daclizumab inhibit IL-2 on activated T cells and thereby help prevent acute rejection of kidney transplants.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Omalizumab inhibits human immunoglobulin E (IgE) and is useful in treating moderate-to-severe allergic asthma.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Monoclonal antibodies for research applications can be found directly from antibody suppliers, or through use of a specialist search engine like CiteAb.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Below are examples of clinically important monoclonal antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In 2020, the monoclonal antibody therapies bamlanivimab/etesevimab and casirivimab/imdevimab were given emergency use authorizations by the US Food and Drug Administration to reduce the number of hospitalizations, emergency room visits, and deaths because of COVID-19.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In September 2021, the Biden administration purchased US$2.9 billion worth of Regeneron monoclonal antibodies at $2,100 per dose to curb the shortage.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] As of December 2021, *in vitro* neutralization tests indicate monoclonal antibody therapies (with the exception of sotrovimab and tixagevimab/cilgavimab) were not likely to be active against the Omicron variant.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Over 2021–22, two Cochrane reviews found insufficient evidence for using neutralizing monoclonal antibodies to treat COVID-19 infections.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] The reviews applied only to people who were unvaccinated against COVID‐19, and only to the COVID-19 variants existing during the studies, not to newer variants, such as Omicron.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] In March 2024, pemivibart, a monoclonal antibody drug, received an emergency use authorization from the US FDA for use as pre-exposure prophylaxis to protect certain moderately to severely immunocompromised individuals against COVID-19.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] Several monoclonal antibodies, such as bevacizumab and cetuximab, can cause different kinds of side effects.
[src:antibody-engineering/antibody-engineering] These side effects can be categorized into common and serious side effects.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] A **bispecific monoclonal antibody** (**BsMAb**, **BsAb**) is an artificial protein that can simultaneously bind to two different types of antigen or two different epitopes on the same antigen.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Naturally occurring antibodies typically only target one antigen.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] BsAbs can be manufactured in several structural formats.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] BsAbs can be designed to recruit and activate immune cells, to interfere with receptor signaling and inactivate signaling ligands, and to force association of protein complexes.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] BsAbs have been explored for cancer immunotherapy, drug delivery, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The original concept of BsAbs was proposed by Nisonoff and his collaborators in the 1960s, including the first idea of antibody architecture and other findings.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In 1975, the problem of producing pure antibodies was solved by the creation of hybridoma technology, and the new era of monoclonal antibodies (MAbs) came.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In 1983, Milstein and Cuello created hybrid-hybridoma (quadroma) technology.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In 1988, the single-chain variable fragment (scFv) was invented by the Huston team to minimize the refolding problems, which contains the incorrect domain pairing or aggregation of two-chain species.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In 1996, the BsAbs became more developed when the knobs-into-holes technology emerged.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] There are many formats of BsAbs, but the two main categories are IgG-like and non-IgG-like.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The main types of manufacturing methods are quadromas, chemical conjugation, and genetic recombination, and each method results in a unique format.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] This format retains the traditional monoclonal antibody (mAb) structure of two Fab arms and one Fc region, except the two Fab sites bind different antigens.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The most common types are called trifunctional antibodies, as they have three unique binding sites on the antibody: the two Fab regions, and the Fc region.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Each heavy and light chain pair is from a unique mAb.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The Fc region made from the two heavy chains forms the third binding site.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] These BsAbs are often manufactured with the quadroma, or the hybrid hybridoma, method.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] However, the quadroma method relies on random chance to form usable BsAb, and can be inefficient.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Another method for manufacturing IgG-like BsAb is called "knobs into holes," and relies on introducing a mutation for a large amino acid in the heavy chain from one mAb, and a mutation for a small amino acid in the other mAb's heavy chain.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] This allows the target heavy chains (and their corresponding light chains) to fit together better, and makes the production of BsAbs more reliable.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] There are other BsAbs that lack an Fc region entirely, and thus leads to relatively simple design strategies.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] These include chemically linked Fabs, consisting of only the Fab regions, and various types of bivalent and trivalent single-chain variable fragments (ScFvs).
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] There are also fusion proteins mimicking the variable domains of two antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The furthest developed of these newer formats are the bi-specific T-cell engagers (BiTEs), which uses the G4S linker to connect two ScFvs-one CD3 antibody ScFv and one tumor-associated antigen (TAA) or tumor-specific ScFv-to redirect T cells to cancer cells for target killing.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Other platforms include tetravalent antiparallel structure (TandAbs) and VH only (Bi-Nanobody).
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The TandAb platform is formed by a tetravalent antibody molecule containing two binding sites for each of two antigens.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In this platform, the reverse pairing of two peptide chains forms a homodimer molecule.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] As an example, AFM11 is based on the TandAbs platform and targets both CD3 and CD19 to achieve therapeutic effects.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] AFM11 showed dose-dependent inhibition of Raji tumors *in vivo*.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The Bi-Nanobody platform forms multi-specific binding through the connection between the VH regions of two or more antibody molecules.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The products that are designed based on this platform are small molecules and these small molecules have high stability and better tissue permeability *in vivo*.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Even though non-IgG-like BsAbs have low molecular weight and thus high tumor tissue permeability, their half-life is relatively short and they require multiple doses.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The binding of a BsAb to its target antigens can lead to a variety of effects.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The most widely used application of this approach is in cancer immunotherapy, where BsAbs are engineered to simultaneously bind a cytotoxic cell and a target (a tumour cell) to be destroyed.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] It is possible to observe the bridging effect that BsAbs have on T cell/cancer cell interactions using label-free live cell imaging.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Catumaxomab, one of the first trifunctional antibodies approved for therapeutic use, binds both CD3 on cytotoxic T cells and EpCAM on human adenocarcinomas.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The Fc region additionally binds to a cell that expresses Fc receptors, like a macrophage, natural killer cell or dendritic cell.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Since the Fc region is still intact, this allows for the BsAb to trigger common immune responses when recognized by an Fc receptor, such as antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity or complement-dependent cytotoxicity.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The growth of tumor cells can be stimulated or modulated by receptor tyrosine kinase (RTKs), including members of the Her family or insulin-like growth factor (IGF).
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The RTKs are therefore preferred targets in cancer therapy.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Although monospecific RTK-targeting IgGs have already been available in the market, such as cetuximab (Erbitux) and panitumumab (Vectibix), both of which are directed against HER1.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] However, cancer cells can switch to a different pathway to escape the growth inhibition generated by blocking one signaling pathway.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] To improve the therapeutic efficacy, simultaneously interfering/blocking of two (or more) RTK signaling pathways, achieved through the mediation of BsAb to inactivate either the RTKs or their ligand, reduces the possibility of the escape mechanisms adopted by the tumor cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In addition, in working with Ebolavirus vaccines, a study has shown that a DVD-Ig antibody can be used to prevent viral escape from the endosome.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Ebolaviruses infect cells by receptor-mediated endocytosis.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Researchers developed DVD-Igs where the outer variable regions bind to the surface glycoproteins of the viral coat and enter the cell with the virus.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] These outer regions are cleaved in the viral endosome, revealing the inner variable regions that then bind to both the virus and internal receptors in the endosome.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Blocking the interaction between the virus and endosomal proteins prevents viral escape from the endosome and further infection.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] As an example, emicizumab (formerly RG6013) is an IgG derivative containing H-chain heterodimerization motifs, which was combined with the common light chain approach to prevent L-chain mispairing issues.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] With a bivalent composition, emicizumab brings two protein antigens together into one complex.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Factor IXa and Factor X in the coagulation cascade are the cognate antigens which are bound by RG6013.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] These two factors are brought together by coagulation factor VIIIa in a healthy individual, while patients with bleeding disorder hemophilia A do not have VIIIa.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Current treatment of this disorder is to supplement the patients with FVIII to reduce bleeding complications.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] But FVIII can be recognized as a foreign protein in these patients due to the absence of this protein and thus an immune response will be generated against this protein.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Besides, FVIII has a short half-life (less than 15 hours) and thus is cleared rapidly.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] However, the humanized BsAb has lower immunogenicity and long serum half-life compared with FVIII and thus provide a better treatment for hemophilia.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Cancer immunotherapy with ordinary monoclonal antibodies does not activate T-lymphocytes because the Fab regions are already used for binding the tumor cells, and this type of cell does not have Fc receptors.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Bispecific antibodies also have a higher cytotoxic potential, and bind to antigens that are expressed relatively weakly.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The effective dose is around 0.01 mg·m−2·d−1 (milligrams per square meter body surface area per day), which is several orders of magnitude lower than with ordinary antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] For non-IgG-like BsAbs, their smaller size allows them to reach antigens usually unavailable to conventional antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] In the case of Ebola vaccines, this method allows the antibody to target intracellular targets not usually accessible by traditional monoclonal antibody treatments.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Additionally, targeting more than one molecule can be useful to circumvent the regulation of parallel pathways and avoid resistance to the treatment.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Binding or blocking multiple targets in a pathway can be beneficial to stopping disease, as most conditions have complicated multifaceted effects throughout the body.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Together with combination therapies, BsAbs are being used more and more to treat certain types of cancers, as, over time, some tumors develop resistances to checkpoint inhibitors and/or co-stimulatory molecules.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Several bsAb drugs have been approved by the US FDA / EMA and over 180 are currently in clinical trials.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The first bispecific antibody to gain regulatory approval, blinatumomab, targets CD19 on B cells and CD3 on T cells, leading to the activation of T cells and the destruction of B cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Additional bispecific antibody drugs have since been approved by the US FDA: emicizumab, amivantamab, tebentafusp, faricimab, teclistamab, mosunetuzumab, epcoritamab, glofitamab.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Among the bsAb programs currently under development, the combination of CD3 and tumor surface targets are the most popular targets pairs.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Other popular targets are HER2, PD-1, PD-L1, EGFR, CTLA-4, etc., which as well as immune targets of PD-1, PD-L1, BCMA, CD47, CTLA-4, LAG-3, 4 -1BB.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Additionally, with the approval of the several new bsAb since 2022, and new mechanisms for improving efficacy like development of hetero-dimer bispecific molecules, several additional possibilities of target pairs have emerged.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] A primary issue accompanying BsAb development since the early stages has been achieving a high ratio of correctly paired bispecific antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Early attempts to produce BsAbs resulted in large amounts of homodimers and other mispaired fragments.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Novel pairing technologies have been developed to increase the heterodimerization rate, leading to higher yields and reduced production costs.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Furthermore, IgG-like antibodies can be immunogenic, which means the Fc region could cause detrimental downstream immune responses caused by cells that are activated by Fc receptors.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The therapeutic use of BsAbs as a whole is still largely in development, with many clinical trials currently ongoing that are determining the efficacy and safety of BsAbs for treatment.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] One major area of concern is the feasibility of administration and management of side effects, where the potential for therapeutic success must be weighed against possible risks.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] The occurrence of side effects primarily depends on the specific antibody, its target, and patient-specific factors.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] These factors have to be individually examined for each patient in order to evaluate the feasibility of a bispecific antibody treatment, and to assess the risk of infusion-related, immune-related, organ-specific, and hematologic side effects.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Bispecific antibodies have a wide variety of applications in diagnosis and therapy.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] BsAbs can be combined with HRPO, can be used in pre-targeting strategies, and can be used to provide better imaging for early detection in diagnosis.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] To treat cancer, BsAbs can target immune cells precisely, help and reactive the immune cells, fine-tune the fate and function of immune cells, improve the tolerance of immune cells, and promote the return to immune homeostasis.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] BsAbs can also be applied to treat other diseases, including hemophilia A, diabetes, Alzheimer's disease, and ophthalmological diseases.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Several bispecific antibodies are presently in clinical use.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Blinatumomab, which targets CD19 and CD3, is used in the treatment of Philadelphia chromosome negative B cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL).
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Emicizumab, which targets clotting factors IXa and X, is used in the treatment of hemophilia A.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Catumaxomab was withdrawn from the European market in 2017 for commercial reasons.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Amivantamab, which targets epidermal growth factor (EGF) and MET receptors, for adult patients with locally advanced or metastatic non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) with epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) exon 20 insertion mutations.
[src:antibody-engineering/bispecific-monoclonal-antibody] Teclistamab, which targets CD3 and B-cell maturation antigen (BCMA), is used in the treatment of multiple myeloma, and zenocutuzumab.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Antibody–antigen interactions are highly specific and those that have high affinity will interact with increased bond strength and trigger downstream immune responses.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The strength of the bond between the epitope of the antigen and the paratope of the antibody will determine the affinity of the interaction.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] There are three CDRs (CDR1, CDR2 and CDR3), arranged non-consecutively, on the amino acid sequence of a variable domain of an antigen receptor.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Three can be found on the Light-chain, named L1 through L3, and three on the Heavy-chain, named H1 through H3.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Since the antigen receptors are typically composed of two variable domains (on two different polypeptide chains, heavy and light chain), there are six CDRs for each antigen receptor that can collectively come into contact with the antigen.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] A typical monoclonal antibody molecule has two antigen receptors and therefore contains twelve CDRs total.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] There are three CDR loops per variable domain in antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Sixty CDRs can be found on a pentameric IgM molecule, which is composed of five antibodies and has increased avidity as a result of the collective affinity of all antigen-binding sites combined.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Since most sequence variation associated with immunoglobulins and T cell receptors are found in the CDRs, these regions are sometimes referred to as *hypervariable regions*.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Within the variable *domain*, CDR1 and CDR2 are found in the variable (V) *region* of a polypeptide chain, and CDR3 includes some of V, all of diversity (D, heavy chains only) and joining (J) regions.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The V region sequence undergoes rearrangement during B-cell development, called somatic recombination.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] This rearrangement of the V-region is where the CDR-L3 and CDR-H3 are encoded and diversified, whereas the other four CDRs are generated in the germ-line.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The diversification of the CDR-H3 will ultimately give antibodies their specificity, and ability to recognize antigens.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Other factors contribute to the antibody-antigen interaction, including amino acid residues.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Residues located in particular positions of a CDR loop are used to classify canonical structures.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Uncharged-polar residues, especially Serine and Tyrosine, are found in CDRs at a high concentration ratio.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] These residues significantly contribute to the direct hydrogen bonds between the antigen and the antibody.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Hydrogen bond interactions will induce the enzymatic activity of an enzyme; therefore, the more hydrogen bonds that are present at the antibody-antigen binding site will result in a stronger, more stable binding structure.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The tertiary structure of an antibody is important to analyze and design new antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The structure and sequence of all six CDRs combined will determine the binding activity of the antigen receptor on an antibody or T-cell receptor.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] CDRs have been separated into canonical classes based on their varying loop lengths, which are commonly used to differentiate the CDRs from each other.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The structural relationship between different length CDRS is based on length-independent components, such as their sequence, and can further characterize CDRs.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The loops, or three-dimensional structures of the non-H3 CDRs (all CDRs but H3) of antibodies have been clustered and classified by Chothia et al. and more recently by North et al.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] Homology modeling is a computational method to build tertiary structures from amino-acid sequences.
[src:antibody-engineering/complementarity-determining-region] The so-called H3-rules are empirical rules to build models of CDR3.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Humanized antibodies are distinct from chimeric antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The latter also have their protein sequences made more similar to human antibodies, but carry a larger stretch of non-human protein.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] There are other ways to develop monoclonal antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] This list covers many of the monoclonals developed for use in humans.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The humanization process takes advantage of the fact that production of monoclonal antibodies can be accomplished using recombinant DNA to create constructs capable of expression in mammalian cell culture.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] That is, gene segments capable of producing antibodies are isolated and cloned into cells that can be grown in a bioreactor such that antibody proteins produced from the DNA of the cloned genes can be harvested *en masse*.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The step involving recombinant DNA provides an intervention point that can be readily exploited to alter the protein sequence of the expressed antibody.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The alterations to antibody structure that are achieved in the humanization process are therefore all effectuated through techniques at the DNA level.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Not all methods for deriving antibodies intended for human therapy require a humanization step (e.g. phage display) but essentially all are dependent on techniques that similarly allow the "insertion" or "swapping-out" of portions of the antibody molecule.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Humanization is usually seen as distinct from the creation of a mouse-human antibody chimera.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] So, although the creation of an antibody chimera is normally undertaken to achieve a more human-like antibody (by replacing constant region of the mouse antibody with that from human) simple chimeras of this type are not usually referred to as humanized.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Rather, the protein sequence of a humanized antibody is essentially identical to that of a human variant, despite the non-human origin of some of its complementarity-determining region (CDR) segments responsible for the ability of the antibody to bind to its target antigen.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Chimeric antibody names contain a *-xi-* stem.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Examples of chimeric antibodies approved for human therapy include abciximab (ReoPro), basiliximab (Simulect), cetuximab (Erbitux), infliximab (Remicade) and rituximab (MabThera).
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] There are also several examples of chimerics currently in clinical trials (e.g. bavituximab, see sortable list for additional examples).
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The humanization process may also include the creation of a mouse-human chimera as an initial step.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] In this case, a mouse variable region is spliced to a human constant region.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The chimera can then be further humanized by selectively altering the sequence of amino acids in the variable region of the molecule.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The alteration process must be "selective" to retain the specificity for which the antibody was originally developed.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] That is, since the CDR portions of the variable region are essential to the ability of the antibody to bind to its intended target, the amino acids in these portions cannot be altered without the risk of undermining the purpose of the development.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Aside from the CDR segments, the portions of the variable regions that differ from those in humans can be corrected by exchanging the appropriate individual amino acids.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] This is accomplished at the DNA level through mutagenesis.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Naming of humanized chimeras includes the stem for both designations (*-xi-* + *-zu-*).
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Otelixizumab is an example of a humanized chimera currently in clinical trials for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis and diabetes mellitus.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] It is possible to produce a humanized antibody without creating a chimeric intermediate.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] "Direct" creation of a humanized antibody can be accomplished by inserting the appropriate CDR coding segments (so-called 'donor', responsible for the desired binding properties) into a human antibody "scaffold" (so-called 'acceptor').
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] As discussed above, this is achieved through recombinant DNA methods using an appropriate vector and expression in mammalian cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] That is, after an antibody is developed to have the desired properties in a mouse (or other non-human), the DNA coding for that antibody can be isolated, cloned into a vector and sequenced (or the DNA can be sequenced directly using single-cell methods).
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The DNA sequence corresponding to the antibody CDRs can then be determined.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Once the precise sequence of the desired CDRs are known, a strategy can be devised for inserting these sequences appropriately into a construct containing the DNA for a human antibody variant.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The strategy may also employ synthesis of linear DNA fragments based on the reading of CDR sequences.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The process requires computer-modelling software to determine which of the antibody's amino acids can be changed from murine-sequence to human-sequence without the changes compromising the conformation of the binding site.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] In the United States, this software was developed, patented, and demonstrated, by Protein Design Labs, Inc. in Mountain View, California, in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Alemtuzumab is an early example of an antibody whose humanization did not include a chimeric intermediate.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] In this case, a monoclonal dubbed "Campath-1" was developed to bind CD52 using a mouse system.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The hypervariable loops of Campath-1 (that contain its CDRs and thereby impart its ability to bind CD52) were then extracted and inserted into a human antibody framework.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Alemtuzumab is approved for treatment of B-cell chronic lymphocytic leukemia and is currently in clinical trials for a variety of other conditions including multiple sclerosis.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] There are technologies that completely avoid the use of mice or other non-human mammals in the process of discovering antibodies for human therapy.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Examples of such systems include various "display" methods (primarily phage display) as well as methods that exploit the elevated B-cell levels that occur during a human immune response.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] These employ the selective principles of specific antibody production but exploit micro-organisms (as in phage display) or even cell free extracts (as in ribosome display).
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] These systems rely on the creation of antibody gene "libraries" which can be wholly derived from human RNA isolated from peripheral blood.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] The immediate products of these systems are antibody fragments, normally Fab or scFv.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] This means that, although antibody fragments created using display methods are of fully human sequence, they are not full antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Therefore, processes in essence identical to humanization are used to incorporate and express the derived affinities within a full antibody.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Adalimumab (Humira) is an example of an antibody approved for human therapy that was created through phage display.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] It is possible to exploit human immune reaction in the discovery of monoclonal antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Simply put, human immune response works in the same way as that in a mouse or other non-human mammal.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Therefore, persons experiencing a challenge to their immune system, such as an infectious disease, cancer or a vaccination are a potential source of monoclonal antibodies directed at that challenge.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] This approach seems especially apt for the development of anti-viral therapies that exploit the principles of passive immunity.
[src:antibody-engineering/humanized-antibody] Variants of this approach have been demonstrated in principle and some are finding their way into commercial development.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Specifically, a gene encoding a protein of interest is inserted into a phage coat protein gene, causing the phage to "display" the protein on its outside while containing the gene for the protein on its inside.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This couples the genotype (gene), phenotype (protein) in the context of an organism (phage) capable of replication.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The phages displaying proteins of interest can then be selected using other proteins or DNA sequences in order to e.g., identify natural protein binding partners or antibodies with a high binding affinity.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The most common bacteriophages used in phage display are M13 and fd filamentous phage, though T4, T7, and λ phage have also been used.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Phage display was first described by George P.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Smith in 1985, when he demonstrated the display of peptides on filamentous phage (long, thin viruses that infect bacteria) by fusing the virus's capsid protein to one peptide out of a collection of peptide sequences.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This displayed the different peptides on the outer surfaces of the collection of viral clones, where the screening step of the process isolated the peptides with the highest binding affinity.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In 1988, Stephen Parmley and George Smith described biopanning for affinity selection and demonstrated that recursive rounds of selection could enrich for clones present at 1 in a billion or less.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In 1990, Jamie Scott and George Smith described creation of large random peptide libraries displayed on filamentous phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Smith and Winter were awarded a half share of the 2018 Nobel Prize in chemistry for their contribution to developing phage display.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] A patent by George Pieczenik claiming priority from 1985 also describes the generation of peptide libraries.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In the case of M13 filamentous phage display, the DNA encoding the protein of interest is inserted into the gene encoding either the minor (pIII) or the major (pVIII) coat protein.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The modified coat protein gene and the rest of the phage genome is then introduced into *E. coli* bacteria, which produce phage virions with the relevant protein fragment as part of their outer coat phage and the DNA encoding for these proteins packaged inside the phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The phages can then be selected using e.g.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] DNA or protein molecules immobilized on the surface of a microplate.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Specifically, phages that display proteins that binds to those targets will remain attached, while others will be removed by washing.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Those that remain can be eluted and amplified by bacterial infection.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The repeated cycling of selection, elution and amplification is sometimes referred to as 'panning', in reference to the enrichment of a sample of gold by removing undesirable materials.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Phage eluted in the final step can be sequenced to identify the selected proteins.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] During amplification step, additional mutations may be introduced into the genes encoding the proteins of interest, enabling a directed evolution protocol.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Elution can be done combining low-pH elution buffer with sonification, which, in addition to loosening the peptide-target interaction, also serves to detach the target molecule from the immobilization surface.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This ultrasound-based method enables single-step selection of a high-affinity peptide.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The DNA encoding a fusion of coat protein and protein of interest is often encoded on a phagemid - a plasmid containing both a bacterial origin of replication and phage attachment sequence.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This allows it to be maintained and amplified in bacteria without producing phage virons.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] When bacterial colony reaches a desired size, a helper plasmid is transformed into the bacteria to supply them with the rest of the phage genome, enabling viron production.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Alternatively, these phage genes can maintained within bacteria under inducible promoters, obviating the need for separate helper plasmid introduction.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Phage display is also a widely used method for *in vitro* protein evolution (also called protein engineering).
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] As such, phage display is a useful tool in drug discovery.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] It is used for finding new ligands (enzyme inhibitors, receptor agonists and antagonists) to target proteins.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The technique is also used to determine tumour antigens (for use in diagnosis and therapeutic targeting) and in searching for protein-DNA interactions using specially-constructed DNA libraries with randomised segments.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Recently, phage display has also been used in the context of cancer treatments - such as the adoptive cell transfer approach.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In these cases, phage display is used to create and select synthetic antibodies that target tumour surface proteins.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] These are made into synthetic receptors for T-Cells collected from the patient that are used to combat the disease.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Recently, M13 bacteriophages were genetically engineered to display an anti-GD2 single-chain variable fragment (scFv) derived from the FDA-approved antibody Dinutuximab on their pIII coat protein.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The engineered phages were subsequently loaded with hundreds of photosensitizer molecules to selectively deliver the payload to GD2-positive neuroblastoma cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Upon activation by light (laser) or ultrasound, the photosensitizers induced targeted and precise killing of GD2-positive cells both in vitro and in vivo.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Competing methods for *in vitro* protein evolution include yeast display, bacterial display, ribosome display, and mRNA display.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The invention of antibody phage display revolutionised antibody drug discovery.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Initial work was done by laboratories at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology (Greg Winter and John McCafferty), the Scripps Research Institute (Richard Lerner and Carlos F.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Barbas) and the German Cancer Research Centre (Frank Breitling and Stefan Dübel).
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In 1991, The Scripps group reported the first display and selection of human antibodies on phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This initial study described the rapid isolation of human antibody Fab that bound tetanus toxin and the method was then extended to rapidly clone human anti-HIV-1 antibodies for vaccine design and therapy.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Phage display of antibody libraries has become a powerful method for both studying the immune response as well as a method to rapidly select and evolve human antibodies for therapy.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Antibody phage display was later used by Carlos F.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Barbas at The Scripps Research Institute to create synthetic human antibody libraries, a principle first patented in 1990 by Breitling and coworkers (Patent CA 2035384), thereby allowing human antibodies to be created in vitro from synthetic diversity elements.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Antibody libraries displaying millions of different antibodies on phage are often used in the pharmaceutical industry to isolate highly specific therapeutic antibody leads, for development into antibody drugs primarily as anti-cancer or anti-inflammatory therapeutics.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] One of the most successful was adalimumab, discovered by Cambridge Antibody Technology as D2E7 and developed and marketed by Abbott Laboratories.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Adalimumab, an antibody to TNF alpha, was the world's first fully human antibody to achieve annual sales exceeding $1bn.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Many genetic sequences are expressed in a bacteriophage library in the form of fusions with the bacteriophage coat protein, so that they are displayed on the surface of the viral particle.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The protein displayed corresponds to the genetic sequence within the phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This phage-display library is added to the dish and after allowing the phage time to bind, the dish is washed.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Phage-displaying proteins that interact with the target molecules remain attached to the dish, while all others are washed away.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Attached phage may be eluted and used to create more phage by infection of suitable bacterial hosts.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The new phage constitutes an enriched mixture, containing considerably less irrelevant phage (i.e. non-binding) than were present in the initial mixture.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Steps 3 to 5 are optionally repeated one or more times, further enriching the phage library in binding proteins.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Following further bacterial-based amplification, the DNA within the interacting phage is sequenced to identify the interacting proteins or protein fragments.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] pIII is the protein that determines the infectivity of the virion. pIII is composed of three domains (N1, N2 and CT) connected by glycine-rich linkers.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The N2 domain binds to the F pilus during virion infection freeing the N1 domain which then interacts with a TolA protein on the surface of the bacterium.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Insertions within this protein are usually added in position 249 (within a linker region between CT and N2), position 198 (within the N2 domain) and at the N-terminus (inserted between the N-terminal secretion sequence and the N-terminus of pIII).
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, when using the BamHI site located at position 198 one must be careful of the unpaired Cysteine residue (C201) that could cause problems during phage display if one is using a non-truncated version of pIII.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] An advantage of using pIII rather than pVIII is that pIII allows for monovalent display when using a phagemid (plasmid derived from Ff phages) combined with a helper phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Moreover, pIII allows for the insertion of larger protein sequences (>100 amino acids) and is more tolerant to it than pVIII.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, using pIII as the fusion partner can lead to a decrease in phage infectivity leading to problems such as selection bias caused by difference in phage growth rate or even worse, the phage's inability to infect its host.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Loss of phage infectivity can be avoided by using a phagemid plasmid and a helper phage so that the resultant phage contains both wild type and fusion pIII.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] cDNA has also been analyzed using pIII via a two complementary leucine zippers system, Direct Interaction Rescue or by adding an 8-10 amino acid linker between the cDNA and pIII at the C-terminus.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] pVIII is the main coat protein of Ff phages.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Peptides are usually fused to the N-terminus of pVIII.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Usually peptides that can be fused to pVIII are 6-8 amino acids long.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The size restriction seems to have less to do with structural impediment caused by the added section and more to do with the size exclusion caused by pIV during coat protein export.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Since there are around 2700 copies of the protein on a typical phages, it is more likely that the protein of interest will be expressed polyvalently even if a phagemid is used.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This makes the use of this protein unfavorable for the discovery of high affinity binding partners.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] To overcome the size problem of pVIII, artificial coat proteins have been designed.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] An example is Weiss and Sidhu's inverted artificial coat protein (ACP) which allows the display of large proteins at the C-terminus.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The ACP's could display a protein of 20kDa, however, only at low levels (mostly only monovalently).
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] pVI has been widely used for the display of cDNA libraries.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] This means that the stop codon in the cDNA is no longer an issue.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, phage display of cDNA is always limited by the inability of most prokaryotes in producing post-translational modifications present in eukaryotic cells or by the misfolding of multi-domain proteins.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] While pVI has been useful for the analysis of cDNA libraries, pIII and pVIII remain the most utilized coat proteins for phage display.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In an experiment in 1995, display of Glutathione S-transferase was attempted on both pVII and pIX and failed.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, phage display of this protein was completed successfully after the addition of a periplasmic signal sequence (pelB or ompA) on the N-terminus.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In a recent study, it has been shown that AviTag, FLAG and His could be displayed on pVII without the need of a signal sequence.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Then the expression of single chain Fv's (scFv), and single chain T cell receptors (scTCR) were expressed both with and without the signal sequence.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] PelB (an amino acid signal sequence that targets the protein to the periplasm where a signal peptidase then cleaves off PelB) improved the phage display level when compared to pVII and pIX fusions without the signal sequence.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, this led to the incorporation of more helper phage genomes rather than phagemid genomes.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In all cases, phage display levels were lower than using pIII fusion.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, lower display might be more favorable for the selection of binders due to lower display being closer to true monovalent display.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In five out of six occasions, pVII and pIX fusions without pelB was more efficient than pIII fusions in affinity selection assays.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The paper even goes on to state that pVII and pIX display platforms may outperform pIII in the long run.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The use of pVII and pIX instead of pIII might also be an advantage because virion rescue may be undertaken without breaking the virion-antigen bond if the pIII used is wild type.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Instead, one could cleave in a section between the bead and the antigen to elute.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Since the pIII is intact it does not matter whether the antigen remains bound to the phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The issue of using Ff phages for phage display is that they require the protein of interest to be translocated across the bacterial inner membrane before they are assembled into the phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Some proteins cannot undergo this process and therefore cannot be displayed on the surface of Ff phages.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In these cases, T7 phage display is used instead.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] In T7 phage display, the protein to be displayed is attached to the C-terminus of the gene 10 capsid protein of T7.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] The disadvantage of using T7 is that the size of the protein that can be expressed on the surface is limited to shorter peptides because large changes to the T7 genome cannot be accommodated like it is in M13 where the phage just makes its coat longer to fit the larger genome within it.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] However, it can be useful for the production of a large protein library for scFV selection where the scFV is expressed on an M13 phage and the antigens are expressed on the surface of the T7 phage.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Databases and computational tools for mimotopes have been an important part of phage display study.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Databases, programs and web servers have been widely used to exclude target-unrelated peptides, characterize small molecules-protein interactions and map protein-protein interactions.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Users can use three dimensional structure of a protein and the peptides selected from phage display experiment to map conformational epitopes.
[src:antibody-engineering/phage-display] Some of the fast and efficient computational methods are available online.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] A **single-chain variable fragment** (**scFv**) is not actually a fragment of an antibody, but instead is a fusion protein of the variable regions of the heavy (VH) and light chains (VL) of immunoglobulins, connected with a short peptide linker of ten to about 25 amino acids.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] Each variable fragment contains framework regions (FWRs), providing stability to the structure, and complementarity-determining regions (CDRs), which are the regions responsible for antigen recognition.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] The linker is usually rich in glycine, which provides flexibility, as well as serine or threonine, that provides solubility.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] The peptide linker can either connect the N-terminus of the VH with the C-terminus of the VL, or *vice versa*, but changes in the orientation of the VH, peptide linker and VL have been described to affect scFv’s affinity and specificity.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] This protein retains the specificity of the original immunoglobulin, despite removal of the constant regions and the introduction of the linker.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] The image to the right shows how this modification usually leaves the specificity unaltered.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] These molecules were created to facilitate phage display, where it is highly convenient to express the antigen-binding domain as a single peptide.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] As an alternative, scFv can be created directly from subcloned heavy and light chains derived from a hybridoma.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] ScFvs have many uses, e.g., flow cytometry, immunohistochemistry, and as antigen-binding domains of CAR-T cells.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] Unlike monoclonal antibodies, which are often produced in mammalian cell cultures, scFvs are more often produced in bacteria cell cultures such as *E. coli*.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] Single-chain variable fragments lack the constant Fc region found in complete antibody molecules, and, thus, the common binding sites (e.g., protein G) cannot be used to purify antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] These fragments can often be purified or immobilized using protein L, since protein L interacts with the variable region of kappa light chains.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] More commonly, scientists incorporate a six histidine tag on the c-terminus of the scFv molecule and purify them using immobilized metal affinity chromatography (IMAC).
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] Some scFv can also be captured by protein A if they contain a human VH3 domain.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] All of these formats can be composed from variable fragments with specificity for two different antigens, in which case they are types of bispecific antibodies.
[src:antibody-engineering/single-chain-variable-fragment] The furthest developed of these are bispecific tandem di-scFvs, known as bi-specific T-cell engagers (BiTE antibody constructs).
